div.p: The intent of this notice is to clear up any confusion regarding grades for this semester. As we have stated a student’s final grade will not be negatively impacted due to the COVID-19 pandemic and the resulting move to a continuous learning plan. The confusion seems to center around grades being negatively impacted. Here is an explanation for how grades will be determined.

On March 13, grades were determined for students. These were 9 weeks grades. The average students had on that day is the lowest final grade that a student will receive. Students do have the opportunity to increase their final grade during the five-week continuous learning plan. Assignments will be provided to students through various methods. All assignments will be graded for every student during this five-week plan. Students failing to turn in assignments will receive zeros (0) for grades on those assignments. If they turn in assignments, those assignments will be graded and the appropriate score will be given. After the five-week continuous learning plan ends all scores for the semester will be used to determine a final grade based on the May 8 date for the end of the semester (just like a regular school semester). Once that score is determined it will be compared to the March 13 grade and the student will receive the higher of the two scores.

If you check your grades (or your child’s grades) during this time it could possibly show a lower average based on scores recorded during this five-week plan. While it is true that they might receive low grades during this plan, their final grade will not be lower than what they had on March 13. Below is an example to illustrate these points.

Student A has a 65 average on March 13. Student A was given 10 assignments during the continuous learning plan. Student A made a 100 on every assignment bringing his May 8 average to 71 for the semester. His final grade for the semester will be a 71/C.

Student B has a 65 average on March 13. Student B was given 10 assignments during the continuous learning plan. Student B receives 0’s (zero) for each assignment. As a result, his May 8 average is 58/F. The student’s final semester grade will be a 65/D since his March 13 average was the higher of the two.

Students are still required to turn in all assignments and all assignments will be graded. The only change in determining final grades this semester is that we will apply the March 13 grade if it benefits the student. If you need additional information please feel free to contact the administration office at (580)875-2568 or 3794.
**Packet Pickup will be Thursday, April 9, 2020, 8:30-12:00, in the following locations:
Middle School – South Parking Lot (on Washington St)
High School – West Parking Lot (on Broadway St)
**No School or Meals - Friday, April 10 & Friday, May 1 (Children no longer have to be seen at the meal pickup line, adults can pickup meals for children)
**Starting Monday, April 13 – “Grab & Go” Meals will now be 8:00 – 11:00
**We are working on a plan to get personal/locker items back to students and will notify at a later date.
Classes using Google Classroom will require students to login with their SCHOOL email address. Format & accessing student email:
Email: first initial last initial last name 4 digit graduation year@waltersps.org
Password: first initial last initial student id (student id can be found in gradebook) Example: ss123456
Students can go to blued.org and click Email (on the left) or they can go to gmail.com. They will login with the complete email address.

div.p: Discrimination is a sociological term referring to the prejudicial treatment of an individual based solely on their membership (whether voluntary or involuntary) in a certain group or category. Discrimination is the actual behavior towards members of another group. It involves excluding or restricting members of one group from opportunities that are available to other groups.

Walters Public Schools does not discriminate on the basis of race, religion, color, national origin, sex, sexual orientation, disability, genetic information, veteran status, marital status or age in its employment, programs and activities and provides equal access to the Boy Scouts and other designated youth groups.
The following person has been designated to handle inquiries regarding the Walters Public Schools’ non-discrimination policies:
Walters High School, 418 S. Broadway, Walters, OK 73572
